<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
Known from three localities in southwestern Greenland. Originally described from New York State under 
<taxonomicName class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Pinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pinus" order="Pinales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Coniferophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Pinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and widespread across North America (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/mycokeys.46.32823" author="Cripps, C" journalOrPublisher="MycoKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" pagination="1 - 54" refId="B9" refString="Cripps, C, Eberhardt, U, Schuetz, N, Beker, HJ, Evenson, VS, Horak, E, 2019. The genus Hebeloma in the Rocky Mountain alpine zone. MycoKeys 46: 1 - 54, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/mycokeys.46.32823" title="The genus Hebeloma in the Rocky Mountain alpine zone." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/mycokeys.46.32823" volume="46" year="2019">Cripps et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
). Similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="H." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="H. mesophaeum" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="mesophaeum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">H. mesophaeum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and therefore likely to be confused and overlooked. Cripps et al. also describe recent records from alpine Rocky Mountains in Colorado and Montana.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="17" type="habitat">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Habitat and ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="17">
Three collections, two of them with 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="Salix" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Salix glauca" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="glauca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">Salix glauca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In the Rocky Mountains, 
<taxonomicName class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Salicaceae" genus="S." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. planifolia" order="Salicales" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="planifolia">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="17">S. planifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was the dominant host (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/mycokeys.46.32823" author="Cripps, C" journalOrPublisher="MycoKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="17" pagination="1 - 54" refId="B9" refString="Cripps, C, Eberhardt, U, Schuetz, N, Beker, HJ, Evenson, VS, Horak, E, 2019. The genus Hebeloma in the Rocky Mountain alpine zone. MycoKeys 46: 1 - 54, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/mycokeys.46.32823" title="The genus Hebeloma in the Rocky Mountain alpine zone." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/mycokeys.46.32823" volume="46" year="2019">Cripps et al. 2019</bibRefCitation>
). Two of the localities are on acid soil.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
